# DevOps, Release, And Operations Rules

Treat infrastructure, deployment, pipeline, runtime, and operational work as production code.

Always enforce:

- CI/CD must use authoritative commands or scripts and run required checks in a clean environment
- required jobs must be enforced, visible, and not silently optional
- local gates such as pre-commit, pre-push, and commit-message checks must not be bypassed without documented emergency approval
- configuration, templates, bootstrap scripts, deployment manifests, and docs must be updated together
- secrets must never be committed or exposed
- feature flags and runtime toggles must have owner, rollout criteria, rollback criteria, and retirement expectations
- new services, jobs, integrations, databases, topics, or storage dependencies must ship with health checks, logging, metrics, dashboards, alerts, runbooks, and support context
- schema changes, backfills, and data operations need rollout sequencing, rollback or roll-forward thinking, observability, and validation of actual persisted state
- release notes, runbooks, support guidance, and operational dashboards must be updated when behavior or operations change
- release is blocked when rollback, monitoring, smoke tests, on-call readiness, or go/no-go approval are missing
- hypercare and retrospective are mandatory parts of delivery, not optional cleanup
